more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ellenor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor  , the result of blending with   Ellen ."]},{"name":"Elenor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]},{"name":"Elinor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Eleanor of Boston was born in 1152, in Boston, Lincolnshire, England. She had at least 2 sons with Thomas de Multon I. She died in 1199, in Moulton, Lincolnshire, England, at the age of 47."},"et":{"1152–1199":"1152–1199","1146–1201":"1146–1201","1166–1240":"1166–1240","1171–Male":"1171–Surnud","about 1171":"umbes 1171","1201":"1201","1146":"1146","1199":"1199","1166":"1166","1152":"1152","1240":"1240","about 1166":"umbes 1166","1171":"1171","Moulton, Lincolnshire, England":"Moulton, Lincolnshire, England","Boston, Lincolnshire, England":"Boston, Lincolnshire, England"},"fi":{"1152–1199":"1152–1199","1146–1201":"1146–1201","1166–1240":"1166–1240","1171–Male":"1171–Kuollut","about 1171":"noin 1171","1201":"1201","1146":"1146","1199":"1199","1166":"1166","1152":"1152","1240":"1240","about 1166":"noin 1166","1171":"1171","Moulton, Lincolnshire, Engla